 0=\frac{d}{dx}\left[ \exp (x) y(x)\right] = \exp (x) y(x) +  \exp (x) y'(x)  
\frac{d}{dx}\left[ \exp (x) y(x)\right]=0
u^{'}=\dfrac{du}{dx}\\ \implies \dfrac{du}{dx}+u=0\\ \implies \dfrac{du}{dx}=-u\\ \implies \int\dfrac{du}{u}=-\int dx\\ \implies \ln|u|=-x+c\\ \implies \boxed{u=Ce^{-x}}
\dfrac{du}{dx}+u=0\\ \implies \dfrac{d(Ce^{-x})}{dx}+Ce^{-x}=0\\ \implies \dfrac{d(e^{-x})}{dx}+e^{-x}=0\\ \implies -e^{-x}+e^{-x}=0\\ \implies 0=0
c\exp(-x)' + c\exp(-x) = -c\exp{-x}+c\exp{-x}=0
